<HL>
   LEISURE &amp; ARTS:
   Time Off: Diversions and Excursions April 3-16
</HL>
<DATE>
04/03/90
</DATE>
<SO>
WALL STREET JOURNAL (J), PAGE A18
</SO>
<LP>
   ART
                                                                                                       

</LP>
<TEXT>
   National Gallery of Art, Washington, D.C. -- "Gardens on
Paper: Prints and Drawings, 1200-1900" -- One hundred works
on paper and vellum -- including woodcuts, engravings,
watercolors, pastels and pen-and-ink drawings -- tracing the
development of the garden as a theme in Western art. The show
also explores differences in national attitudes toward
gardens.
                                                                                                       

   Fourth Street at Constitution Avenue NW, through July 22.
American Museum of Natural History, New York: "Black
Achievers in Science" -- Biographies, photographs and
personal memorabilia focus on the accomplishments of more
than 100 black Americans in the fields of life sciences,
physical sciences, mathematics and computer sciences, and
engineering. Among the 16 achievers profiled in depth are
George Washington Carver (1864-1943), the botanist and
agricultural scientist who developed more than 300 products
from peanuts and 100 from the sweet potato; and Patricia S.
Cowings, a psychophysiologist with NASA who devised
biofeedback methods used by astronauts. Central Park West at
79th Street, through June 10.
                                                                                                       

   O.K. Harris, New York: "Sgraffiti: Works by Hai Knafo" --
Seventeen oversized pieces demonstrating the ancient
technique of "sgraffito" on an unusual 20th-century canvas,
fake brick paneling. This New York artist, using woodcutting
tools, creates his designs by scratching the white facade of
the paneling to reveal the brown masonite underneath. 83 West
Broadway, Manhattan, April 7-28.
                                                                                                       

   Valentine Museum, Richmond, Va.: "Smoke Signals:
Cigarettes, Advertising, and the American Way of Life" --
Through the example of the Richmond cigarette industry, this
exhibit of 400 objects as well as vintage TV and radio
commercials examines how changes in technology and marketing
have influenced American life since the 1880s. 1015 East Clay
St., April 6-Oct. 8.
                                                                                                       

   DANCE
                                                                                                       

   Eiko and Koma: The three works this Japanese-born couple
will dance during its Joyce Theater debut -- "Memory," "Rust"
and "Passage," -- are all New York premieres. But if past
performance is any indication, expect poetic imagery and
hypnotically slow motion. Tonight -- April 8, 175 Eighth
Avenue at 19th St. (212) 242-0800. After this, the pair can
be seen in San Antonio, Texas. (Carver Center), April 12-15;
Taos, N.M. (Taos Community Auditorium), April 16-17;
Albuquerque, N.M. (KiMo Theater), April 18-19; St. Louis
(Center of Contemporary Arts), April 2021; and Boston
(Emerson Majestic Theater), May 1-6.
                                                                                                       

   MUSIC
                                                                                                       

   Metropolitan Opera: Dwarfs, giants, gods and mere mortals
squabble and sing as Wagner's "Ring" cycle returns to the
repertoire. Three cycles are offered this spring, all
featuring superwoman Hildegard Behrens as the warrior maiden
Brunnhilde. Hear her hojotoho for the first time this
Saturday (in person or on the national Texaco radio
broadcast) when "Die Walkure" revives with James Morris as
her father Wotan. James Levine conducts and Jessye Norman
sings Sieglinde. (The first cycle continues April 13 and 21.
Dates for the second cycle are April 23, 24, 26 and 28; for
the third, April 30, May 1, 3 and 5.)
                                                                                                       

   The somewhat shorter-tuned "Fledermaus" by Johann Strauss
also returns to the repertoire with Barbara Daniels and
Thomas Allen, April 7, 10, 16, 19. Both productions are at
Lincoln Center, 65th and Broadway. (212) 362-6000.
                                                                                                       

   New York Rock and Soul Revue: Four distinctive pop
stylists -- Donald (Steely Dan) Fagen, Phoebe Snow, Patti
Austin and Michael (Doobie Brothers) McDonald -- get together
tomorrow to sing some of the R&amp;B classics that influenced
them, as well as several of their own greatest hits. Beacon
Theatre, 74th and Broadway, Manhattan. (212) 496-7070.
