<HL>
   Westinghouse Gets
   $500 Million Job
   For British Plant
   ----
   By Gregory Stricharchuk
   Staff Reporter of The Wall Street Journal
</HL>
<DATE>
04/03/90
</DATE>
<SO>
WALL STREET JOURNAL (J), PAGE C15
</SO>
<CO>
   WX ENE J.MHI
</CO>
<IN>
ELECTRICAL COMPONENTS AND EQUIPMENT (ELQ)
</IN>
<LP>
   PITTSBURGH -- Westinghouse Electric Corp. said it received
a $500 million order to supply power generating equipment to
Enron Power Corp., a unit of Enron Corp., Houston.
   The equipment, to be produced by Westinghouse and its
joint venture partner, Mitsubishi Heavy Industries of Japan,
will be used in Britain's $1 billion Teesside Power Project.
</LP>
<TEXT>
   The contract is significant because it provides the
six-month-old Westinghouse-Mitsubishi joint venture a key
foothold in the European market and an opportunity to
demonstrate whether the two companies can work together under
tight deadlines. The plant is scheduled to begin commercial
operation in early 1993.
   Westinghouse said its initial order is for eight
169-megawatt combustion turbine-generators and two
216-megawatt steam turbine-generators. The company also said
it was awarded an exclusive option to supply 10 additional
combustion turbine-generators.
   A Westinghouse spokeswoman declined to break out the
amounts it will receive under each order, but some people in
the industry valued the initial contract at between $200
million and $250 million. Westinghouse, which has been
expanding its North American capacity to meet the revival in
demand for combustion turbines, wouldn't say how much of the
equipment would be produced by Mitsubishi.
   Westinghouse said Britain's Brush Electrical Machines Ltd.
will also provide some of the steam turbines.
   Last year Westinghouse said its orders for power
generation equipment jumped about 20%. Those bookings
amounted to about 2,000 megawatts of generation, according to
Westinghouse's recently released annual report. The
Westinghouse spokeswoman said the company currently has a
backlog of power generation equipment orders of about $1
billion.
   Enron's order roughly equals all of Westinghouse's power
generation equipment orders received last year. Teesside
alone is a 1,725 megawatt natural gas-fired cogeneration
power plant, said to be one of the world's largest.
   Enron will design and build the project on the northeast
coast of England. Electricity produced at the plant will be
sold to ICI Chemicals &amp; Polymers Ltd. and other customers in
the United Kingdom, Westinghouse said. The plant will be
England's first independent power producer.
   Westinghouse also has significant interests in
broadcasting, financial services, over-the-road refrigeration
and electronic systems.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO>
WSJ900403-0112
</DOCNO>
<DOCID>
900403-0112.
</DOCID>
<HL>
   Labor Letter:
   A Special News Report on People
   And Their Jobs in Offices,
   Fields and Factories
   ----
   By Albert R. Karr
</HL>
<DATE>
04/03/90
</DATE>
<SO>
WALL STREET JOURNAL (J), PAGE A1
</SO>
<CO>
   LABOR TRB
</CO>
<IN>
TRANSPORTATION, TRUCK AND SHIP LINES, RAILROADS (TRA)
AUTOMOBILES (AUT)
INSURANCE (INS)
</IN>
<GV>
EXECUTIVE (EXE)
CONGRESS (CNG)
LABOR DEPARTMENT (LBR)
FEDERAL GOVERNMENT (FDL)
</GV>
<LP>
   A FUNDING PINCH hampers states' jobless-pay operations.
   A $121 million fiscal 1990 shortfall in federal funds,
caused by a rising unemployment-compensation workload and
Gramm-Rudman budget cuts, is forcing Indiana to slash costs
20%. Claims offices were trimmed to 26 from 43, with 100 of
740 workers laid off. Massachusetts, New York, New Jersey and
Texas also plan office closings, layoffs or reduced hours,
mainly for temporary help used for peaks.
</LP>
<TEXT>
   In New Hampshire, where the workload has nearly tripled
from last year, the staff is down 7%. Officials "steal"
claims workers from other jobs, such as tax collecting; but
waits in claims lines, usually a half hour, still climb to
three to five hours. California shelves control efforts that
try to avoid wrong payments or nonpayments.
   A House bill would add funding, but the Bush
administration opposes release of more of the
employer-financed funds, short of "a dire emergency."
                                                                                                       

   THE WHITE HOUSE favors naming a rail-labor emergency
board.
   Officials say the president would form the panel to avert
a nationwide railroad strike. Railroads and 12 negotiating
unions both want the board, and the National Mediation Board
probably will declare a bargaining impasse soon. The next
step is the emergency panel. Health costs, soaring over 15% a
year, are the biggest issue; the railroads want worker $100
deductibles and $2,000 out-of-pocket medical-bill limits
raised.
   The roads seek work-crew cuts, freedom to assign work as
they wish and the right to contract out more, among
work-rules changes; they also want to trim wages, unions say.
The unions want 5% pay boosts every six months, job
protection in short-line sales and an end to some
subcontracting.
                                                                                                       

   CHILD-LABOR POLICE will step up enforcement still more.
   New sweeps of employers are planned -- one before school
is out and another in the fall. A recent three-day blitz
found 9,300 violations including kids working late or long
hours, instead of the 7,000 estimated at the time, officials
say. Fines will reach $2.5 million, rather than $1.8 million.
Violations will be announced in bunches, starting today.
   The Labor Department's Employment Standards and
Occupational Safety and Health agencies will sign an
agreement this week for investigators at both agencies to
swap data on child-labor and safety violations. "Sweat-shop"
investigators often find chained rear doors, for instance, a
danger in a fire. Similar plans are afoot with state
worker-safety agencies.
   In a labor pinch, "some employers cut legal corners" by
filling low-level jobs with children, says William Brooks,
the Employment Standards chief.
                                                                                                       

   NO FOLLOW-THROUGH? Though 73% of 491 employers polled by
placement consultant Right Associates expect a skilled-labor
shortage, three-fourths don't have a plan to keep most-needed
workers. Of those who foresee problems, 44% predict higher
training costs and 43% expect increased pay and benefits to
recruit new workers.
                                                                                                       

   THE MINIMUM WAGE rose to $3.80 an hour Sunday, but the
Labor Department estimates that employers can pay the new
short-term $3.35 training wage for as many as 3.7 million
teen-agers. But finding youths at the minimum already is
tough. "You're not going to find people . . . to work for a
sub-minimum," says Arby's.
                                                                                                       

   THE SILVER LINING? The business of finding jobs for fired
executives will climb 15% to 17% this year, topping $400
million, the Association of Outplacement Consulting Firms
says. Lenders, builders and developers, reeling from weak
real-estate markets, contribute to the placement surge.
                                                                                                       

   AUTO WORKER RETIREES plump for automatic cost-of-living
adjustments to their pensions. They lobby for the UAW to make
retiree COLAs a priority bargaining item. Canadian auto
workers won the benefit from auto makers in 1987. But only 3%
of all U.S. pensioners have such COLAs, the Pension Rights
Center says.
                                                                                                       

   GETTING TOUGHER: Firms push harder to share health costs
with workers.
   Fully 45% of 1,943 employers surveyed by consultant Foster
Higgins in 1989 required employee contributions to premiums
for individual coverage, up from 39% in 1988, and 75%
required contributions for dependents, compared with 69%.
Employee shares had held steady since '86, declining slightly
in '87 and '88. Average worker contributions eased a bit in
1989, to $23.03 for employee-only and $69.46 for dependent
coverage.
   But more than a fourth of the companies plan to increase
the employee contribution this year. Individual deductibles
of more than $100 were required by 60% of employers and
family deductibles of more than $300 by 49%, up from 51% and
42%, respectively, in 1988.
   About 72% of employers required workers to pay part of
hospital charges, compared with 66% in 1988.
                                                                                                       

   THE CHECKOFF: Nearly half of 3,500 workers surveyed by
consultant Wyatt Co. said their managers are too tolerant of
poor employee performance -- not by the surveyed workers, of
course. . . . The Tribune Co., its New York Daily News locked
in a bitter labor-contract battle, cancels a congressional
reception in Washington after unions threaten to picket the
party. . . . Record revenue trimmed the Pension Benefit
Guaranty Corp. 1989 deficit 30% to $1 billion; but the PBGC
faces possible loss of a Supreme Court case to LTV, which has
$2 billion in underfunded plans.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
