<HL>
   Politics &amp; Policy:
   Erskine Henderson Appears to Lead
   Candidates for Appointment to SEC
   ----
   By Kevin G. Salwen
   Staff Reporter of The Wall Street Journal
</HL>
<DATE>
04/03/90
</DATE>
<SO>
WALL STREET JOURNAL (J), PAGE A22
</SO>
<IN>
SECURITIES INDUSTRY (SCR)
</IN>
<GV>
SECURITIES AND EXCHANGE COMMISSION (SEC)
EXECUTIVE (EXE)
</GV>
<LP>
   WASHINGTON -- The White House is close to nominating
Erskine Henderson, a New York securities lawyer, to the
Securities and Exchange Commission, administration sources
said.
   Mr. Henderson, who would be the second black commissioner
in the SEC's history, is a special counsel at Skadden, Arps,
Slate, Meagher &amp; Flom, a New York law firm known for its
mergers and acquisitions work. Mr. Henderson specializes in
securities and takeover litigation, and colleagues at the
firm said he has experience in accounting law although he
isn't an accountant.
</LP>
<TEXT>
   White House sources insisted that no decision has been
made, and that the background check on Mr. Henderson hasn't
been completed. One administration insider said that it could
be two months before the White House offers a nomination, but
that Mr. Henderson heads the short list of candidates. Others
mentioned include Washington lawyers Bruce Mendelsohn, Albert
Beveridge and Mahlon Frankhauser.
   If nominated, Mr. Henderson would fill the Democratic
commission slot left open by the January resignation of
Joseph Grundfest, a staunch free-marketeer who is now a
Stanford University Business School professor.
   The recent swearing-in of former Time Warner Inc. lawyer
Philip Lochner Jr. gives Chairman Richard Breeden a virtual
hammerlock on the five-member commission. It isn't clear how
the nomination of Mr. Henderson might affect agency policy.
   While Mr. Lochner hasn't yet voted at an open meeting, his
statements at his Senate confirmation hearing showed a
similar political bent to that of the chairman. Mr. Breeden
has pushed hard to expand the SEC's enforcement program and
to broaden the agency's jurisdiction over disclosure by
brokerage firms. Another commissioner, Mary Schapiro, often
sides with Mr. Breeden in commission votes.
   Edward Fleischman, who predates Mr. Breeden at the
commission by several years, has begun to emerge as the
agency's most dissident voice. He disagrees with the chairman
on the SEC's most controversial issue -- the chairman's
desire to regulate stock-index futures, which are now
overseen by the Commodity Futures Trading Commission.
   Mr. Henderson, 40 years old, couldn't be reached for
comment. But colleagues describe him as a team player without
much ideological fervor. He has been a lawyer at Skadden Arps
for about 11 years following his graduation from Columbia
University Law School.
   He has represented a number of companies in takeover
situations, including Hammermill Paper Co. in the company's
effort to fend off a foray early in Carl Icahn's career.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO>
WSJ900403-0108
</DOCNO>
<DOCID>
900403-0108.
</DOCID>
<HL>
   Business World:
   Continental Bank's Pilots Say
   They're Above the Credit Clouds
   ----
   By Tim W. Ferguson
</HL>
<DATE>
04/03/90
</DATE>
<SO>
WALL STREET JOURNAL (J), PAGE A21
</SO>
<IN>
BANKS (BNK)
</IN>
<LP>
   CHICAGO -- No credit chill is felt in the second-floor
office of Continental Bank's chairman. Coatless on a cool
rainy day, Thomas Theobald and his deputy for corporate
deals, Vice Chairman Garry Scheuring, remain hot on leverage
as a tool for repairing U.S. competitiveness.
   Since arriving from Citicorp three years ago, Mr.
Theobald, 52, has transformed the big, money-center
institution known as Continental Illinois into a smaller
business bank. Few retail depositors now traipse to tellers
in the grand lobby outside the chairman's quarters. The new
Continental sees itself in the Morgan Guaranty mold, but
reaching out to 2,000 companies instead of only the Fortune
200. Despite the pinch on commercial borrowing in the
American economy, no one's crying ouch here.
</LP>
<TEXT>
   "There's adequate liquidity around," says Mr. Scheuring.
"In some pockets, there have been banks that pulled back. I
don't see it in the target customer base that we look at.
Certainly smaller home builders that rely on S&amp;Ls don't have
the credit facilities that they used to have. At the other
end, larger transactions, HLTs (high-leverage) will be harder
to do. There will be more diligence and screening, but I
think today good businesses have finance available. But at
the edge, small companies, this is a factor."
   Mr. Scheuring, who at 50 has risen in 26 years with the
bank, suggests what that "factor" means: "We have an economy
that's growing at about 1%. It doesn't take much to make 1% a
minus 1%. I have a hard time reading that because this is
really unparalled in our experience -- when there's adequate
money but it doesn't want to go. You have enough of that
happen I suppose you do have the possibility of a negative.
On the other hand, it puts a discipline in the system that's
probably OK. Our customers (include) a couple of the largest
home builders in California. They have no problem. Their
small 4- or 5-building competitor who has no equity and wants
to borrow it all can't do it."
   Mr. Theobald, meantime, isn't criticizing recent rule
making for whatever contraction is being felt at banks: "In
Boston, you might say it's the regulators, but when you talk
about Bank of America or Wells Fargo (which he sees
retreating from some areas), those are market-induced
strategic decisions." In his view, government is to blame in
the longer run, for restrictions on interstate banking: "If
you go back to the political fault, it was sectioning off the
country into these local markets. It ruined the Texas banks,
it's doing a lot of of damage to the New England banks. Those
are dangerous portfolio inducements." Continental, still
among U.S. banking's Top 25, is expanding out from its
region.
   One regulator nod to the "market" has the chairman wary.
That's the increasing resort to "mark to market" accounting
of high-yield assets, which Continental uses in client
restructurings. "Philosophically, I support mark-to-market,"
Mr. Theobald says. "But if you look at the practical,
near-term proposals, they are bastardizations of the idea.
What most of them say is let's pick some selective asset and
mark it down to market. But we'll certainly not permit mark
up of other assets, or we will not permit you to adjust
liabilities according to their value. If you take a British
bank . . . every one, two or three years, they revalue their
real estate. Or Japanese banks have equity securities that
are worth a lot more than book values. If you want to say to
any one of us, let's mark the whole balance sheet to market,
fine."
   In any case, he says, "We have several times done detailed
analyses here of marking everything to market, and
ironically, it doesn't come out much different. The law of
large numbers." But with thrifts forced to sell everything
the regulators consider "junk" and mutual-fund redemptions
aggravating the price slide in that market, valuation is
dicier. "If you're an S&amp;L or a commercial bank," Mr. Theobald
says, "you might legitimately ask whether it's reasonable to
have the kind of mentality that's allegedly caused all kinds
of distortions in the industrialized economy visited on them.
You know -- the market's value today is the answer, the
truth."
   That's not Wall Street talking. Mr. Theobald emphasizes
he's a company banker. The 146 high-yield deals that
Continental has done don't reflect a desire to empower
financiers -- just the opposite, he says. "People who are
focused on some business, live it and die it, generally do
better than people who work off spread sheets and financial
analysis. A lot of what I see as the virtue of the LBOs, HLTs
and so on is that they are leading to more focused
companies." Even the takeovers? "If you look at the RJR
transaction, and say what was the beginning to end of it, it
was going to be spin-outs. While initially it was gathering
in all these food assets, it was structured in such a way
that they had to redistribute them."
   In fact, fundamentals dominate in Mr. Theobald's world.
But don't high real interest or "hurdle" rates shape a
business's decision to buy new machinery vs. take cash out?
"I've never seen it in my career. You can analyze a market to
read in some of those macro factors, but I don't see
businessmen making their decisions with overt weight given to
that kind of consideration. If there's more demand for a
product, they want to expand. If somebody's available to buy
that makes a great synergy, they want to buy. Most of them
look through currency rates and interest rates. And I'm not
sure they're wrong, because currencies and interest rates
fluctuate so much that if you're making a 5- or 10-year
decision, what are you going to do?"
   Mr. Theobald disparages congressional credit allocation
incentives, such as moves to raise reserve requirements for
high-yield lending, as "really Third World stuff." Meanwhile,
his bank may finally have other Third World stuff, the
writedown of bad loans to backward nations, behind it. Also,
it isn't too exposed in real estate. Yet Continental's share
price is at a two-year low. Malaise is industrywide, but
analysts worry that new HLTs will be scant and existing ones
rocky.
   This bank's particular claim to notoriety remains the 1982
federal bailout of its depositors, the biggest in U.S.
financial history and the hall mark of the "too big to fail"
doctrine that chills the climate for deposit-insurance
reform. (Smaller banks say they need the existing guarantee
of at least $100,000 per deposit in order to compete with
major rivals that enjoy de facto backup.) But Mr. Theobald
offers a footnote on that affair: Internal calculations
suggest that had the feds not stepped in, maybe $1.5 billion
of Continental's $40 billion in deposits would have been
lost.
   A haircut that slight suggests it's more feasible to let
the marketplace discipline risky financiers -- and avoid
artificial credit crunches -- than Washington now believes.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO>
WSJ900403-0107
</DOCNO>
<DOCID>
900403-0107.
</DOCID>
<HL>
   Technology and Health:
   Psyllium's Ability
   To Cut Cholesterol
   Backed by Studies
   ----
   By Kenneth H. Bacon
   Staff Reporter of The Wall Street Journal
</HL>
<DATE>
04/03/90
</DATE>
<SO>
WALL STREET JOURNAL (J), PAGE C4
</SO>
<CO>
   K
</CO>
<IN>
FOOD PRODUCTS (FOD)
</IN>
<LP>
   WASHINGTON -- Three new studies financed by Kellogg Co.,
Battle Creek, Mich., found that cereal laced with the grain
psyllium reduces cholesterol. But the findings may touch off
a fresh round of health claims and counterclaims similar to
the dispute over the benefits of oat bran.
   All three of the new studies tested people with high
cholesterol levels who had already been put on
low-cholesterol diets. The addition of psyllium, which is
high in soluble fiber, further reduced cholesterol levels and
lowered cholesterol more than other fibers, including oat
bran, they found.
</LP>
<TEXT>
   As a result, the Kellogg-financed researchers said, cereal
containing psyllium can reduce the risk of heart disease by
fighting cholesterol-clogging of the arteries. Kellogg, which
orchestrated a big public-relations effort to promote the new
studies, sells Heartwise, the only cereal with psyllium sold
nationwide by a major cereal company. But psyllium isn't
without controversy. Last year, the Food and Drug
Administration looked into the safety of its use in large
quantities in cereal. In response, General Mills Inc. took a
psyllium-based cereal off the market.
   Psyllium, also known as flea wort, is grown primarily in
India. It has been used for years by Procter &amp; Gamble Co. in
its laxative Metamucil. The new studies, which were released
at the annual meeting of the Federation of American Societies
for Experimental Biology here, all concluded that psyllium is
safe in cereals, although some of those in the tests reported
such effects as gas, bloating and cramping -- symptoms common
to a sudden increase in fiber consumption.
   All three studies measured the impact of psyllium after
the subjects had been put on a low-fat diet and fed cereal
supplied by Kellogg. The studies were conducted at the
University of Kentucky, George Washington University, and the
University of Massachusetts Medical School in Worcester.
   A Kellogg spokeswoman said, "We're encouraged by the
studies," but she wouldn't say how they might influence the
company's marketing plans for Heartwise, which isn't a big
seller, or other new cereals.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO>
WSJ900403-0106
</DOCNO>
<DOCID>
900403-0106.
</DOCID>
<HL>
   Abreast of the Market:
   Stocks Fall on Investors' Concern
   About Tokyo, 1st-Quarter Reports
   ----
   By Craig Torres and David Wilson
   Staff Reporters of The Wall Street Journal
</HL>
<DATE>
04/03/90
</DATE>
<SO>
WALL STREET JOURNAL (J), PAGE C2
</SO>
<IN>
STOCK MARKET, OFFERINGS (STK)
STOCK INDEXES (NDX)
</IN>
<LP>
   NEW YORK -- Investors sold stocks on concerns about bad
first-quarter earnings, the plunging Tokyo stock market, and
the belief that interest rates won't fall anytime soon.
   The Dow Jones Industrial Average fell 6.76 to 2700.45.
Standard &amp; Poor's 500-Stock Index fell 1.24 to 338.70. For
the quarter, the S&amp;P 500 finished down 3% on a total return
basis. Volume totaled 124,360,000 shares on the New York
Stock Exchange, where declining issues swamped advancers
1,122 to 434.
</LP>
<TEXT>
   Byron Wien, U.S. investment strategist for Morgan Stanley,
boosted the cash position in his model all-stock portfolio to
10% yesterday from 3%. "I felt that sentiment had driven the
market," he explained. "To move up the next leg, the market
needs help from interest rates. While I am optimistic, I
wanted hope and reason to be in better balance."
   Mr. Wien's colleague, Barton Biggs, chairman of Morgan
Stanley Asset Management, said he recently raised cash levels
to 15% in his global portfolio, reducing the equity portion
to 45% from 55%. The bond portion remains at 40%.
   Mr. Biggs said he is concerned about the decline in Tokyo
shares. "I think a 32% decline in the biggest market in the
world is an event," he said. "I think our market is de-linked
from ordinary performance in Japan, but not from a financial
panic." He added that margin calls and credit scares in Japan
could be two factors that create selling in other markets.
   "I think there are going to be aftershocks; it will ripple
through all markets," said Mr. Biggs, who added that he wants
more cash on hand to hunt for values if stock markets tumble.
   Disappointing earnings news from Network Equipment
Technologies sent the stock plummeting 6 3/8 to 23 1/2 on 1.8
million shares. The company said it expects revenue and net
income for the March quarter to be significantly lower than
it had anticipated, with per-share earnings possibly falling
short of 33 cents a year earlier.
   The first quarter's dividend activity confirms the dismal
state of corporate profits, according to Arnold Kaufman,
editor of Standard &amp; Poor's "Outlook" newsletter.
   "There has been a downtrend in corporate profits since
1988 and dividends are starting to reflect that very
clearly," said Mr. Kaufman.
   S&amp;P, surveying 7,557 companies, found that dividend
increases shrank to 414 in the first quarter, down 20.5% from
the same period a year earlier. The number of dividend
decreases and omissions rose 64.5% to 79 in the first quarter
from the same period in 1989.
   "We are not going to see an improvement through the rest
of this year," Mr. Kaufman predicted.
   Several of the put warrants on Tokyo Nikkei stock index
topped the most active list on the American Stock Exchange
yesterday. Nikkei put warrants allow investors to bet on a
decline in the Tokyo stock market. The Denmark issue closed
up 3/4 to 11 3/4; the January 1993 Salomon Brothers issue
rose 5/8 to 10 7/8; a February 1993 issue from Salomon gained
7/8 to 11 3/4, and the Bankers Trust issue rose 1 to 25 3/4.
   American General dropped 1 7/8 to 36 3/4 on 1.2 million
shares. Torchmark withdrew its bid to acquire the company for
$50 a share in cash and stock and said it would wage a proxy
fight for five board seats. American General turned down
Torchmark's slate, however, contending it wasn't submitted by
a deadline for nominations set in its bylaws. Torchmark rose
1/4 to 45 1/2.
   Pfizer slipped 1 5/8 to 59 on 1.1 million shares. Barron's
magazine reported that the company faces a potentially "huge
liability" if it loses a lawsuit, filed by a recipient of one
of the heart valves once made by its Shiley unit. The suit
seeks damages for anxiety resulting from the news of problems
with the valve. The report included several documents
indicating that the company was aware of potential hazards
with the valve but urged doctors not to publicize them.
   Fleet/Norstar Financial Group fell 5/8 to 21 1/4 on 1.8
million shares after disclosing that it is being examined by
federal and state banking regulators. The company said it
might have to boost its loan-loss reserve, based on their
findings.
   Unocal rose 1 3/4 to 33 5/8 on 1.3 million shares amid
continued speculation that British Petroleum may be
interested in taking over the company. BP declined comment;
the stock fell 1 3/4 to 63 as a sell-off on the London market
hurt shares of British companies traded in the U.S.
   Motorola rose 1 to 66 after a federal court stayed an
injunction against sales of the company's flagship
microprocessor. The ban had been imposed as part of the
court's decision in a patent-infringement case between
Motorola and Hitachi.
   Digital Equipment gained 3/8 to 77 1/8 in advance of
today's expected introduction of new engineering
workstations. Compaq Computer, which unveiled a high-speed
controller for use in computer networks, climbed 2 1/8 to 97
5/8.
   UAL fell 7/8 to 161 1/8 amid continuing discussions about
a buy-out bid from the three major unions at its United
Airlines unit. The group is offering cash and securities
valued at $185 a share.
   Wheelabrator Technologies rose 1 1/2 to 35. Waste
Management agreed to increase its stake in the company to 55%
from 22% through a stock swap. Waste Management rose 1/8 to
34 1/4.
   Mortgage &amp; Realty Trust rose 5/8 to 8 1/8 after reaching a
preliminary agreement with a group of lenders for $425
million in financing. Shares of the trust dropped sharply
last month after it didn't make a payment on a note issue;
Mortgage &amp; Realty said the funding would permit it to make
that payment, among other things.
   General Development dropped 1 7/8 to 4. The company said
it hadn't been able to reach agreement on a $60 million
credit facility over the weekend and it is considering a
Chapter 11 bankruptcy filing, along with alternatives.
   West Point-Pepperell fell 1 1/4 to 37. The company that is
holding investor William Farley's stake in Pepperell
defaulted on $796 million in bank debt and on interest
payments due on $705 million in subordinated debt.
   Hotel Investors Corp. fell 1/2 to 4 1/2 after reporting a
$60.3 million loss for 1989, reflecting a $55.8 million
provision for losses on its hotel and gaming properties and
goodwill. The company also cut back an agreed-upon sale of
some of its hotel interests.
   The American Stock Exchange Market Value Index fell 2.38
to 359.37. Volume on the American Stock Exchange was
14,490,000. There were 405 issues declining and 165
advancing.
   New Line Cinema rose 1/2 to 11 3/8. The company said its
new movie, "Teenage Mutant Ninja Turtles," grossed
approximately $25.4 million in its first weekend at the box
office.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
