<HL>
   REVIEW &amp; OUTLOOK (Editorial) -- Asides:
   Ancient History
</HL>
<DATE>
04/03/90
</DATE>
<SO>
WALL STREET JOURNAL (J), PAGE A20
</SO>
<GV>
CONGRESS (CNG)
</GV>
<LP>
   Bad news for Washington, if not the Republic: There's
evidence that for most American kids, Washington is history.
A report just out by the National Assessment of Educational
Progress says only about one-third of polled eighth graders
know that Congress makes the laws or could identify the
presidential veto. About half know that the U.S. is a
representative democracy or understand the separation of
powers. Still, there may be reasons for these results.
   Maybe they'd be better able to recognize their government
if someone asked them what a $500 billion omnibus
appropriation bill was. Or a continuing resolution. Most kids
in grade school probably think local judges make the nation's
laws. How is a 13-year-old supposed to know what a
presidential veto is if nobody's spotted more than one or two
since 1974? As to the U.S. being a representative democracy,
is this question related to the 99% re-election rate in the
House of Representatives? The reason some of their parents
don't vote is that increasing numbers of Members have no
opponent in the general election.
</LP>
<TEXT>
   We do wonder about one thing, though. If 33% know that
Congress makes laws, what does the other 66% think Congress
does?
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO>
WSJ900403-0084
</DOCNO>
<DOCID>
900403-0084.
</DOCID>
<HL>
   REVIEW &amp; OUTLOOK (Editorial):
   Pennsylvania's Brave Experiment
</HL>
<DATE>
04/03/90
</DATE>
<SO>
WALL STREET JOURNAL (J), PAGE A20
</SO>
<CO>
   ACK
</CO>
<IN>
TENDER OFFERS, MERGERS, ACQUISITIONS (TNM)
</IN>
<LP>
   We are tempted beyond endurance, so we hereby
enthusiastically cheer passage of Pennsylvania's proposed
anti-takeover, anti-proxy bill. It is indeed an awful piece
of legislation. Just yesterday, SEC Chairman Richard Breeden
warned that Pennsylvania's bill would "shield management from
investor oversight," and he threatened to use federal laws to
invalidate parts of the bill. Nonetheless, in the interest of
financial science, we say bring it on.
   There is nothing like federalism's 50 petrie dishes to
show which state corporate laws attract capital and jobs and
which spook investors and handicap local economies.
Pennsylvania is about to make the ultimate sacrifice on
behalf of this knowledge.
</LP>
<TEXT>
   At the moment, it looks as if managers of companies
incorporated in Pennsylvania -- fourth among the Fortune 500
-- will get full defenses against any market or stockholder
pressures. The bill speeding through the legislature this
week would disgorge the profit from a stockholder who sells
within 18 months of launching any kind of bid for the
company. This is pure expropriation.
   Moreover, instead of the ancient duty to maximize share
price, directors fighting off bids could consider the
interests of "stakeholders" (employees, suppliers and the
like) above the interests of stockholders. Fiduciary duty,
RIP.
   The most extraordinary feature of the bill is that it
would even make proxy contests, which are always difficult,
prohibitively expensive. The bill says that anyone -- except
managers -- who initiates a proxy must be prepared to buy the
company at a price set by a judge. This provision applies
even if the proxy is not to take over the company but only,
say, to change accounting firms. Any stockholder who launches
a proxy and solicits 20% of the votes would have to tender
for all shares.
   You might wonder why the country's most radical
anti-takeover bill comes during a lull in the takeover
battles and the problems in the junk-bond market. The
explanation -- as with nearly all the prior state legislation
-- is that this bill is to benefit one particular firm
against an out-of-state bidder. Here, Pennsylvania's
Armstrong World Industries has been eyed by the Belzberg
family of Canada.
   Not everyone is happy with the prospect of corporate
protectionism and permanently entrenched managers becoming a
way of life in the Keystone state. The head of investing for
Pennsylvania's own $9.6 billion State Employees' Retirement
System says that if the bill passes he'll oppose any more
investments in companies incorporated in the state. "I could
not invest another penny in them because of my legal duties
to present and future retirees," Kenneth Mertz told state
legislators. "We should not have a law that prevents me from
investing our retirement funds in Pennsylvania companies --
money that belongs to Pennsylvanians."
   Opponents of the bill point to a letter from a regional
office of the Federal Trade Commission and its Bureau of
Economics. It notes that studies by the SEC and others have
shown that share prices fall after enactment of state
anti-takeover bills. Share prices dropped by 1% in New York,
2% in Ohio and between 4% and 6% in Indiana. Prices seem to
fall in proportion to the severity of the legislation, so
Pennsylvania shares could tumble even more.
   But as we say, Pennsylvania is perfectly free to pass any
legislation it likes now that the Supreme Court has chosen
not to invalidate these laws. As social experiments go, we
can't think of many more important than determining the costs
of draconian legal barriers to takeovers and proxy battles.
To this end, Pennsylvania is about to enact a very bad bill.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO>
WSJ900403-0083
</DOCNO>
<DOCID>
900403-0083.
</DOCID>
<HL>
   Trammell Crow
   Big Refinancing
   Is Completed
   ----
   By Christi Harlan
   Staff Reporter of The Wall Street Journal
</HL>
<DATE>
04/03/90
</DATE>
<SO>
WALL STREET JOURNAL (J), PAGE A6
</SO>
<IN>
REAL ESTATE, REITS, LAND DEVELOPMENT (REL)
</IN>
<LP>
   DALLAS -- Trammell Crow Co., as part of an ongoing
restructuring of its debt and operations, completed a $456
million refinancing deal with Equitable Real Estate
Management Inc.
   While the deal is well shy of the $600 million that
Trammell Crow originally sought from Equitable Real Estate,
it will enable the giant real estate developer to cut the
interest it pays on the debt by almost 2.5 percentage points,
while injecting badly needed cash into poorly performing
projects in the Southwest.
</LP>
<TEXT>
   The bulk of the financing will be used to pay off existing
debt on about 90 Trammell Crow properties, which will be
pledged as collateral for the new debt. About $90 million in
remaining cash will be used to pay down Trammell Crow's debt
on another 60 properties that have been unprofitable,
according to Robert Whitman, chief financial officer for
Trammell Crow.
   When the company first approached Equitable Real Estate
about a year ago, it had hoped to clear about $113 million in
cash to pay down the debt on 100 ailing projects. Mr. Whitman
said that list was pared to 60 through the sales of some
properties and improvements in market conditions. Other
properties were rejected by Equitable Real Estate because of
environmental problems, and still others were mortgaged by
lenders who were unwilling to accept an early pay down, Mr.
Whitman said.
   The refinancing with Equitable Real Estate will enable
Trammell Crow to reduce its interest rates from 11.3% to
about 8.8%, Mr. Whitman said. The deal will also put about
10% of Trammell Crow's Southwest projects in the hands of a
single lender and one that has financed Crow projects since
the early 1950s.
   The properties involved in the Equitable deal were
originally financed by some 30 lenders, many of whom are now
feeling pressure from federal regulators to reduce their
exposure to real estate losses. And the stock market added
pressure of its own in early March, when rumors of loan
defaults by Trammell Crow drove down stock prices of some
large bank holding companies.
   Equitable Real Estate President Douglas A. Tibbetts said
the pressures didn't shake his company's commitment to the
refinancing.
   "Despite the rumors that came out recently, we maintained
our comfort level," he said.
   The financing is being provided by the general account of
Equitable Real Estate's parent, Equitable Life Assurance
Society of the U.S., and is the second large refinancing hat
the company has done for Trammell Crow. In 1987, Equitable
Real Estate refinanced the Dallas Market Center for $450
million.
   The properties covered by the current refinancing are
predominately in Texas, Arizona and Colorado, and 70% of them
are industrial or warehouse buildings. About 20% of the
properties are retail centers and the remainder is made up of
office buildings.
   The properties involved in the deal represent about 3% of
Trammell Crow's national holdings of about $15 billion in
real estate. The company ranks as the nation's largest
residential builder and second largest commercial builder.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
