<HL>
   New Securities Issues
</HL>
<DATE>
04/03/90
</DATE>
<SO>
WALL STREET JOURNAL (J), PAGE C17
</SO>
<CO>
   EUROP F.CNT F.CLC CCI
</CO>
<IN>
BOND MARKET NEWS (BON)
FINANCIAL, ACCOUNTING, LEASING (FIN)
REAL ESTATE, REITS, LAND DEVELOPMENT (REL)
SAVINGS AND LOANS, THRIFTS, CREDIT UNIONS (SAL)
HEAVY CONSTRUCTION; INDUSTRIAL AND COMMERCIAL (CON)
BANKS (BNK)
</IN>
<LP>
   The following were among yesterday's offerings and
pricings in U.S. and non-U.S. capital markets, with terms and
syndicate manager, as compiled by Dow Jones Capital Markets
Report:
                                                                                                       

                        MUNICIPALS
                                                                                                       

</LP>
<TEXT>
   Alaska Housing Finance Corp. -- $104 million general
purpose revenue bonds, due June 1 and Dec. 1, 1990-1997, were
tentatively priced by a Dean Witter Reynolds Inc. group to
yield from 6.15% in 1990 to 7% in 1996 and 1997. Current
interest serial bonds are priced at par to yield from 6.15%
for bonds due Dec. 1, 1990 to 7% for bonds due June 1, 1996
and Dec. 1, 1996 and June 1, 1997. There are no term bonds.
Bonds maturing in 1991 are priced to yield 6.30% for bonds
due June 1, 1991 and 6.35% for bonds due Dec. 1, 1991. Bonds
maturing in 1992-1996 are due both June 1 and Dec. 1 and
carry the same yield each of those years. The bonds are
secured by a letter of credit from the Industrial Bank of
Japan Ltd., Los Angeles Agency, and a Triple-A rating is
expected from Moody's Investors Service Inc.
   Imperial Irrigation District, California -- $102.5 million
certificates of participation, due Nov. 11, 1990-1999, 2007
and 2009, with capital appreciation bonds due 2000-2004, were
tentatively priced by a PaineWebber Inc. Group to yield from
5.80% in 1990 to 7.23% in 2007. Current interest serial bonds
are priced to yield from 5.80% in 1990 to 6.80% in 1999.
There are $21.67 million term bonds priced to yield 7.23% in
2007 and $17.2 million term bonds priced to yield 7.20% in
2009. Capital appreciation bonds are priced to yield to
maturity from 6.85% in 2000 to 7.05% in 2003 and 2004. The
bonds are rated Double-A by Moody's and Double-APlus by
Standard &amp; Poor's Corp.
                                                                                                       

                         MORTGAGES

   Citibank N.A. -- Issued a $210 million mortgage
pass-through issue, Citibank Conduit Series 1990-A, backed by
a pool of residential mortgage loans. The issue is expected
to be rated Triple-A by both Moody's and S&amp;P on the strength
of a 100% unconditional and irrevocable financial guaranty
insurance policy from Financial Security Assurance, according
to a news release from FSA. The underlying mortgage portfolio
is typical of uninsured pass-through issues, which are
usually rated Double-A, FSA said. The mortgage loans are
predominantly on owner-occupied, single-family detached
houses. Further details were unavailable.
                                                                                                       

                         EUROBONDS
                                                                                                       

   European Community (agency) -- 350 million European
Currency Units of 10 5/8% Eurobonds due April 20, 1995,
priced at 101.60 to yield 10.66 pc less fees, via Paribas
Capital Markets. Fees 2.
   Caisse Nationale des Telecommunications (France) -- 1
billion French francs of 10% Eurobonds due April 25, 2000, to
yield 10.02% after fees, via Credit Commercial de France.
Guaranteed by Republic of France. Fees 2.
   Instituto de Credito Oficial (Spain) -- $250 million of
floating rate notes paying interest at 2 1/2 basis points
below the six-month London interbank bid rate, priced at par
and reoffered at 99.88, via Credit Suisse First Boston.
Statutory guarantee by Kingdom of Spain. Fees 0.17.
   Credit Lyonnais Australia (French parent) -- $50 million
(Australian) of 15 1/2% Eurobonds due May 4, 1992, priced at
101.95, via Hambros Bank Ltd. Guaranteed by Credit Lyonnais.
Fees 1 1/4.
</TEXT>
