<HL>
   Heard on the Street:
   Brazil's Sweeping Measures Aimed at Inflation
   Could Hurt Earnings of Several U.S. Firms
   ----
   By John R. Dorfman
   Staff Reporter of The Wall Street Journal
</HL>
<DATE>
04/03/90
</DATE>
<SO>
WALL STREET JOURNAL (J), PAGE C2
</SO>
<CO>
   LATAM AA CHA F GM UK BZF
</CO>
<IN>
STOCK MARKET, OFFERINGS (STK)
HEARD ON THE STREET (HRD)
INTERNATIONAL ECONOMIC NEWS AND STATISTICS (IEN)
</IN>
<LP>
   NEW YORK -- Grab hold of your in-box. Give it a quick,
violent jerk, and watch the papers scatter. That will give
you a rough idea of what the economy of Brazil looks like at
the moment.
   Intent on stopping runaway inflation, new President
Fernando Collor de Mello has instituted a series of sweeping
measures, including restricting people's access to their own
money held in bank accounts. By yanking the economy to a
sudden halt, instituting a new currency, and slapping on
price controls (among other steps), Mr. Collor hopes to break
inflation's back.
</LP>
<TEXT>
   But the process will be painful for many Brazilians.
According to analysts, it may also hurt earnings for several
U.S. companies with big operations in Brazil, such as
Aluminum Co. of America, Champion International, Ford,
General Motors and Union Carbide.
   Securities firms are scrambling to assess the impact.
Early off the starting line is PaineWebber, weighing in with
a report by strategist Edward M. Kerschner (with economic
analyst William Dinning).
   The Collor plan "goes well beyond what anyone had imagined
he would do," Mr. Kerschner says. "Of the four possible
reform plans that incoming finance minister Ms. Zelia Cordoso
de Mello had drawn up, Collor went for the most radical. . .
. (It) has thrown the seventh largest economy in the world
into waters rarely charted by any economy.
   "For Brazil, a very steep recession seems likely," Mr.
Kerschner concluded. "Most economic activity has ceased. For
example, General Motors did not sell a single car in Brazil
last week."
   Aluminum Co. of America derives "at least 15% of its
operating income" in Brazil, estimates Clarence Morrison,
metals analyst with Prudential-Bache. An Alcoa spokesman says
he thinks that figure is "a little high." But he confirmed
that Brazil accounted for 11% of Alcoa's net income last
year.
   The spokesman said that Alcoa has been "down there for
about 25 years. It's been good for us and we think in the
long run it will continue to be good for us." However, he
said "what's going on presents some challenges" to Alcoa near
term. He declined to estimate the possible earnings impact.
   Union Carbide has a large industrial gases operation in
Brazil, notes Ted Semegran, a chemical analyst with Shearson
Lehman Hutton. He says a rapid slowing of Brazil's economy
could hurt the business, and is also worried about the
possibility of write-downs connected with currency
devaluation.
   Mr. Semegran emphasized that it's too early to know what
will happen. But if the Brazilian operations went to
break-even, he figures it might clip as much as 10% off Union
Carbide's earnings.
   John R. MacLean, president of Union Carbide Industrial
Gases Corp. (which includes the industrial gas operations in
the U.S., as well as Latin America) says he thinks Brazil's
government is "doing the right thing." He added, "We would
endure any kind of short-term pain" to do business in a
Brazil that was rid of hyperinflation.
   The effects on first-quarter earnings will be very small,
Mr. MacLean said. In the second quarter, he said, "there will
be some negative short-term effects," which he declined to
estimate. He agreed with Mr. Semegran's assessment that if
the Brazilian operations went to break-even, Carbide's
earnings might fall about 10%.
   Champion International, a forest products company, derived
about 20% of its net income last year from Brazilian
operations, according to the PaineWebber report. A Champion
spokesman couldn't be reached for comment yesterday.
   Ford was selling more than 2,000 cars a week in Brazil
last year, and GM was selling more than 3,000 a week.
According to PaineWebber, both companies have stopped
producing cars and sent their staffs home on full pay. "This
could be a significant negative for the earnings of both
companies," PaineWebber said, adding that GM is losing money
on North American auto operations and relies on sales outside
North America for profits.
   Spokesmen for GM and Ford both said yesterday that it's
too early to assess the earnings impact of the Brazil
situation. According to figures provided by a Ford spokesman,
Brazil accounted for about 1.7% of Ford's world-wide truck
and car sales last year.
   The stock most directly affected by Brazil's financial
crisis is Brazil Fund, an investment fund that invests in
Brazilian companies and trades on the New York Stock
Exchange. On March 20, the fund announced it would "halt
temporarily the determination of the fund's net asset value."
That halt is still in effect, and the fund's portfolio
manager declined to be interviewed yesterday.
   Yet last month, Brazil Fund shares dropped only 15%, to 11
from 13. That decline was surprisingly mild, considering that
the Brazilian stock market had fallen 40% to 50%, says
Charles H. Brandes, chief investment officer of Brandes
Investment Management in San Diego.
   Mr. Brandes bought Brazil Fund shares at 7 last year, when
they traded at about a 40% discount from net asset value, or
NAV (the value of the shares in the portfolio). He rode the
shares up to 16, then sold because they were at a premium to
NAV.
   Mr. Brandes guesses that Brazil Fund's NAV now is $9 to
$10 a share. He is watching the stock but says, "It hasn't
gone low enough for me yet." He would be eager to buy if the
shares again fall to a 40% discount, which at the moment
would equal a share price of 6 to 7.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO>
WSJ900403-0068
</DOCNO>
<DOCID>
900403-0068.
</DOCID>
<HL>
   Executive Predicts
   Oil Prices to Stay
   Close to Inflation
   ----
   By Caleb Solomon
   Staff Reporter of The Wall Street Journal
</HL>
<DATE>
04/03/90
</DATE>
<SO>
WALL STREET JOURNAL (J), PAGE C14
</SO>
<CO>
   RD SC MDEST
</CO>
<IN>
DOW JONES INTERVIEW (CEO)
PETROLEUM (PET)
</IN>
<LP>
   NEW ORLEANS -- Despite forecasts by some experts, oil
prices won't rise on the average much faster than the rate of
inflation over the next several years, a top executive of
Royal Dutch/Shell Group predicted.
   Through the 1990s, that will translate into about a $1 a
year added to the per-barrel price of oil, Sir Peter Holmes,
chairman of Shell Transport &amp; Trading, one of the two owners
of the giant Royal Dutch/Shell Group, said in an interview.
</LP>
<TEXT>
   Sir Peter conceded that prices could continue to move like
"a roller coaster," bouncing around within an upwardly moving
$4 range. But he said the Shell Group is forecasting a
generally moderate overall trend because it believes the
Organization of Petroleum Exporting Countries will expand
production to meet growing world demand. OPEC, which
currently supplies about 45% of the non-Communist world's
oil, is considered pivotal to future price movements.
   Recently, a number of forecasters have projected world oil
demand will grow faster than production capacity, triggering
a spike that could double prices by the mid-1990s. Current
world oil prices range from about $16 a barrel to $20 a
barrel.
   In taking a more conservative view, Sir Peter also cited
OPEC's apparent desire to avoid a rerun of past rapid price
escalations that produced world turmoil. "They don't want to
see prices run away," he said. In particular, he said,
"Kuwait is determined to keep prices low."
   The Shell Group estimates that OPEC's largest producer,
Saudi Arabia, will meet its goal of expanding daily
production capacity to 8.5 million to 10 million barrels from
current capacity of 7.8 million. The other OPEC members with
the potential and desire to boost output -- Iran, Iraq, and
the United Arab Emirates -- also will meet their goals early
in the 1990s, he said.
   As a result, Sir Peter predicted, OPEC's daily production
will stay at a comfortable level in relation to capacity. "If
OPEC production remains at around 80% of installed capacity,
it is unlikely you will see prices surge either upward or
downward," he said. In the past, when OPEC output crossed the
80% threshold, he said, prices became far more volatile.
   OPEC's Secretary-General Subroto has been saying that OPEC
will need to spend $60 billion over the next several years to
raise its capacity to meet demand for its oil. Subroto has
asked for help from international oil companies, but Sir
Peter doesn't think many countries will seek such outside
financing.
   "I don't think the Saudis, Kuwait or the U.A.E. will need
any at all," he said. "Over five years, $60 billion isn't
that much."
   Sir Peter said Iran and Iraq may need some help and
disclosed that the company has talked with Iraq officials.
"They have been welcoming and then less welcoming," he said.
   The Shell Group sees big opportunities, however, in the
Soviet Union. "We're trying real hard to get in," Sir Peter
said. "It will happen but I think it will be slow." He said
current Soviet oil technology is outdated. "They are
operating with techniques we used 30 and 40 years ago," he
said. "A couple of decades doesn't sound like much, but in
our industry that's the stone age."
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO>
WSJ900403-0067
</DOCNO>
<DOCID>
900403-0067.
</DOCID>
<HL>
   LEISURE &amp; ARTS:
   Where the Buffalo Don't Roam
   ----
   By Ruth Rudner
</HL>
<DATE>
04/03/90
</DATE>
<SO>
WALL STREET JOURNAL (J), PAGE A18
</SO>
<LP>
   Yellowstone National Park, Wyo.
   The solitary buffalo crossed an open field near Rescue
Creek Trail. Enormous, old, he walked stiff-legged and
without hurry. His massive head with its thick, curling,
almost-black hair bobbed up and down, sniffing the earth,
delicately picking up bits of grass to eat. On his shoulders
and hump the curling hair had turned pale cinnamon, as it
often does in old bulls, while his slender back and hips were
the same deep brown they had always been. Noble ice-age
beast, he ambled through sagebrush, carrying in his ancient
heart all the centuries of his existence. He has been in
Yellowstone since the last glaciers left, 10,000 years ago.
</LP>
<TEXT>
   The Rescue Creek trailhead is not far from the park's
north entrance, at Gardiner, and the boundary between the
park and the state of Montana. Would the old bull cross to be
greeted by a hunter's gun? A hunt takes place when there is a
chance buffalo (more correctly, bison) will wander onto
Montana ranchlands. Because they can carry brucellosis, which
causes cattle to abort if they come into contact with the
fresh afterbirth of an aborted bison fetus, ranchers are
understandably concerned if bison cross the boundary.
   But buffalo do not recognize boundaries. Their "captivity"
inside the park goes against their migratory nature. When
stressed by severe winters, nature prevails. They have left
the park periodically over the years, although never in such
great numbers as two winters ago when 569 -- half the herd --
were shot, nor in the presence of such media coverage.
   It was February when I watched the old bull. There was a
sense of spring in the air. Perhaps, I thought, we'll make it
through the winter with no hunt beyond the one buffalo shot
early in the season. But within a few weeks there was new
snow, and 20 bison left the park near West Yellowstone. The
hunt was on, and off, and on again as bison wandered back and
forth across the border. "Probably the number of animals
taken this year will be quite small," said John Cada,
regional wildlife manager for the Montana Department of Fish,
Wildlife and Parks. "If you can sting them a little when they
first come out," he explained, "they're more apt to go back.
If you let them lounge around, they begin to think of the
area as home. It's easier to keep them out of a new area than
run them out of home."
   In mid-March three bison were shot. Animal-rights
activists were on the scene to disrupt the event. Two
protesters were arrested, one on charges of misdemeanor
assault, the other for interfering with a lawful hunt. The
activists called their cohorts' behavior "inappropriate," but
reiterated their belief that the real crime is killing bison.
After that hunt the protesters tried herding bison back into
Yellowstone. Park officials warned them away, saying the
attempt constituted harassment of wild animals, which could
not be permitted in the park.
   It probably wouldn't have had much effect anyway. While
some bison can be moved for short periods of time, basically
bison will go only where bison want to go. Numerous attempts
to keep them in the park -- hazing, cattle guards, fences,
recorded wolf-howls, sirens, tin-can rattles and cracker
shells, flashing lights, rubber bullets -- have not worked.
Besides that, any plan designed to keep animals in the park
runs counter to park policy of keeping animals wild by
allowing them natural movement through their natural habitat.
   "Just as no one is saying we should keep all the elk in
the park, no one should be saying bison must be kept in the
park," said Ed Lewis, executive director of the Bozeman-based
Greater Yellowstone Coalition. "Yellowstone has the only
free-roaming bison population and any management plan must
allow for it to continue."
   GYC has been instrumental in initiating the possibility of
a viable management plan by bringing together the Park
Service, U.S. Forest Service and the Dept. of Fish, Wildlife
and Parks, the agencies that deal with bison in the
ecosystem. They also have succeeded in getting the agencies'
agreement to maintain a core herd of 200 to 300 bison,
enough, according to park spokeswoman Joan Anzelmo, that
visitors will see bison herds in the park.
   Shooting a buffalo isn't really terrific sport. It's sort
of like shooting a cow. "They are pastoral animals," said
Bozeman sculptor Brian Persha, who is outraged at the hunt's
denial of the buffalo's nature. Mr. Persha, who feels that
GYC's attempt to find an alternative to the hunt must be
supported, is donating proceeds from the sale of his work to
them. Making multiples of his sculpture for the first time,
Mr. Persha has created three bronzes, one of them a small,
reclining buffalo. Resting, waiting, eternal, his buffalo is
an eloquent statement of that great animal's quiet power.
   It is also one approach to what, at times, seems an
impossibly polarized problem -- to shoot or not to shoot.
"Population control has to happen," the wildlife department's
Mr. Cada said, "either by ranger or other hunters, or
rounding them up and selling them to the slaughterhouses.
Thirty years ago we were doing the same thing with elk. For a
similar reason. We didn't have a place for those Yellowstone
elk. Even though it took us a few years, our goal was to
acquire key pieces of winter range. We'll still hunt elk, but
instead of a firing line at the park boundary, we can manage
them.
   "I look at this as an opportunity. Things have to be major
to get support and we're talking about a major commitment
from society. We hope that society says, `Hey, I'm willing to
put my money where my mouth is and authorize Congress to buy
range out of the park.'"
   Leaving the old bull at Rescue Creek, I drove on to the
Lamar Valley. Broad, wild, silent, filled with light and
time, the valley opens before you as you come out of Lamar
Canyon like some primeval dream of land. It was here that the
Buffalo Ranch was established in 1907, five years after
captive herds of plains buffalo were introduced into
Yellowstone in an attempt to reestablish a wild herd. The
remnant of the wild mountain buffalo that had always lived in
Yellowstone mingled and prospered under the improved
protection that came with the newcomers. The experiment
successful, the ranch was disbanded in the 1950s. Lamar is
one of three winter ranges now used by Yellowstone's buffalo.
   The Lamar River ran dark and sparkling between banks of
wind-polished snow. Groups of buffalo were spread along its
length, their tracks crisscrossing the broad flats extending
south and east of the river. Wherever the animals had
stopped, the snow was churned, scuffed, pocked and pawed.
Buffalo are as evident where they are not as where they are.
   The road through Lamar is one of the few park roads that
is plowed. Not many cars had passed as I watched the buffalo,
but as I drove back, I found myself in a traffic jam.
Buffalo, larger than my car, walked up and down the middle of
the road, then ran across it, stopped on the opposite side,
returned to the road, crossed back and, finally, ran a few
feet alongside the road before disappearing from my view
behind a small rise. How thoroughly this place is theirs, I
thought.
   ---
   Ms. Rudner is a free-lance writer based in Bozeman, Mont.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
