<HL>
   International Brief -- N.V. Amev:
   Dutch Insurer Plans Merger
   With Groupe of Belgium
</HL>
<DATE>
04/03/90
</DATE>
<SO>
WALL STREET JOURNAL (J), NO PAGE CITATION
</SO>
<CO>
   N.AME B.AGG
</CO>
<IN>
TENDER OFFERS, MERGERS, ACQUISITIONS (TNM)
INSURANCE (INS)
</IN>
<LP>
   N.V. Amev, the third-largest Dutch insurance company, and
Groupe AG, Belgium's biggest insurer, announced plans to
merge, creating Europe's 12th-largest insurer in terms of
premium income. A final pact is expected before year end.
   Amev and Groupe each would own 50% of a joint venture,
with operating units initially separate, designed to
strengthen both as the European Community moves toward freer
cross-border competition. Groupe would pay 10.7 billion
Belgian francs ($305.3 million) to Amev over 10 years to
cover the difference in Amev's greater value. The two
parents, which also have moved into banking, would keep
separate stock market quotations.
</LP>
<TEXT>
   The combined companies would have annual revenue of about
$7 billion, assets of $35 billion, and shareholders' equity,
including unrealized gains on assets, of $4 billion. They
have a combined stock market value of about $4.6 billion.
   Amev posted a 28% rise in 1989 profit to 354.8 million
guilders ($186 million), or 5.78 guilders a share, from 276.2
million guilders, or 4.97 guilders a share, in 1988.
</TEXT>
