<DOCNO>
WSJ900403-0040
</DOCNO>
<DOCID>
900403-0040.
</DOCID>
<HL>
   Two Retail Units
   Of Campeau Post
   Losses for 4 Weeks
   ----
   By Jeffrey A. Trachtenberg
   Staff Reporter of The Wall Street Journal
</HL>
<DATE>
04/03/90
</DATE>
<SO>
WALL STREET JOURNAL (J), PAGE A8
</SO>
<CO>
   CMAFC
</CO>
<IN>
RETAILING (RET)
BANKRUPTCIES (BCY)
EARNINGS (ERN)
</IN>
<LP>
   NEW YORK -- Federated Stores Inc. said its Federated and
Allied retailing units incurred losses totaling $45.8 million
for the four weeks ended March 3. The figure excludes the
costs of filing for Chapter 11 status.
   The Campeau Corp. unit said the performance "exceeded its
expectations" for the first complete month of operation since
filing Jan. 15 for protection from creditors under Chapter 11
of the federal Bankruptcy Code.
</LP>
<TEXT>
   But Federated didn't provide financial results for
February 1989, so a direct comparison couldn't be made
independently.
   Federated Stores Inc. was formerly known as Campeau
(U.S.). Late last week, Federated filed for Chapter 11
status, calling the filing a "procedural step" as part of its
reorganization plan. Federated Stores remains fully owned by
Campeau, based in Toronto.
   The Federated Department Stores Inc. division incurred
losses of $29.9 million on revenue of $277 million. Its
outlets include Bloomingdale's, Abraham &amp; Strauss, Burdines,
Lazarus and Rich's/Goldsmith's.
   The Allied Stores Corp. division had a loss of $15.9
million on revenue of $156.7 million. Its stores include Bon
Marche, Jordan Marsh, Maas Brothers/Jordan Marsh, and
Stern's.
   Although February wasn't profitable for Federated Stores,
it was a marked improvement compared with the losses incurred
for the 20 days ended Feb. 3, 1990. In that period, Federated
had a loss of $37 million on revenue of $158.6 million; the
Allied unit posted losses of $19 million on $77.3 million of
revenue.
   Altogether, the Allied and Federated units have incurred
losses of $101.8 million since filing for Chapter 11 status.
"Half of that loss is interest expense being accrued by the
companies at the same rate as was paid in the pre-petition
period," said a Federated Stores representative.
   "It's a lot of money to lose in such a short period," said
Howard Bloom, president of Chetta B. Inc., a women's apparel
maker. "We are shipping to them, however, and I would like to
continue doing business with them."
   Other manufacturers, as well as one important factoring
company, also expressed support for the Allied and Federated
units.
   "February is generally a weak retailing period," said
Frank DeRita, senior vice president, Congress Talcott Corp.,
a major factoring company. "There is a relative safety net
because they have enough cash on hand to meet trade
obligations in April and beyond. Considering the filing, and
this period in the retail cycle, this is to be expected."
Factors buy retail payables from manufacturers at a discount,
thus providing them with cash.
   "It's fairly normal to show losses like this in a
restructuring," added Bud Konheim, president of Nicole Miller
Ltd., a women's apparel supplier. "What we want to know is
whether the bleeding has stopped. If this performance means
they've cleaned up their inventory, that's fine. The history
of retailers coming out of Chapter 11 bankruptcy proceedings
isn't great."
   Federated Stores said that it ended the February selling
period with "stocks in better shape" than anticipated.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO>
WSJ900403-0039
</DOCNO>
<DOCID>
900403-0039.
</DOCID>
<HL>
   Canadian Bank
   Sells 50% Stake
   In Australia Bank
   ----
   By Robert Melnbardis
   Staff Reporter of The Wall Street Journal
</HL>
<DATE>
04/03/90
</DATE>
<SO>
WALL STREET JOURNAL (J), NO PAGE CITATION
</SO>
<CO>
   T.RY A.ANZ WBK NAB FREST
</CO>
<IN>
BANKS (BNK)
TENDER OFFERS, MERGERS, ACQUISITIONS (TNM)
</IN>
<LP>
   TORONTO -- Royal Bank of Canada sold its 50% stake in its
Australian bank for 200 million Australian dollars (US$150
million) in the first part of a A$3.4 billion merger (US$2.6
billion) between a big bank and an insurance concern in
Australia.
   Royal Bank retreated from full-service retail banking in
Australia by selling its half-interest in National Mutual
Royal Bank Ltd. to Australia &amp; New Zealand Banking Group, or
ANZ. National Mutual Life Association of Australasia Ltd.,
Royal Bank's joint-venture partner in the 130-branch bank,
also sold its stake to ANZ. Total proceeds for the
transactions were A$400 million.
</LP>
<TEXT>
   The sale of the bank was the first leg of a proposed
merger in which ANZ will pay A$3.4 billion for a 51% stake in
National Mutual Life. The merger, if accepted by shareholders
and policyholders and approved by the Australian government,
would create Australia's largest financial-services concern,
said David Trude, analyst at First Boston Corp. It also would
protect ANZ from a raid by its competitors, who are mainly
Westpac Banking Corp. and National Australia Bank Ltd., of
Melbourne, he said. ANZ said the merged entity will have A$91
billion of group assets and A$39 billion under management.
   National Mutual Life policyholders will be asked to
approve the merger with ANZ on May 29, with combined
operations set to begin on Oct. 1. Following the merger, ANZ
will ask its shareholders to change its name to ANZ-NM
Banking and Insurance Group Ltd. ANZ is a large banking and
financial services group and National Mutual Life is
Australia's second-largest life insurance concern. Both are
based in Melbourne.
   In a statement, Australian government Treasurer Paul
Keating said he approved in principal ANZ's acquisition of
National Mutual Royal Bank, but said he would consider
various policy issues regarding the union of ANZ and National
Mutual Life. It is likely that Mr. Keating will approve the
ANZ-National Mutual Life merger because the two concerns
don't operate to a significant degree in the same businesses,
Mr. Trude said.
   Mr. Keating said that in the event the merger doesn't go
ahead, ownership of National Mutual Royal Bank will revert to
National Mutual Life.
   Although National Mutual Royal Bank "exceeded
expectations" on performance, Toronto-based Royal Bank said
it sold its interest in the bank to accommodate its
joint-venture partner.
   "I would think that they are happy to get out of there,"
said First Boston's Mr. Trude, adding that foreign banks
created when the Australian government granted 16 new banking
licenses in 1985 have faced tough competition from Australian
domestic banks. He noted that National Mutual Royal Bank was
one of the more successful new entrants in the deregulated
Australian banking sector.
   A spokesman for Royal Bank said the bank had invested
about A$140 million of capital in National Mutual Royal Bank.
He said Royal Bank's focus in recent years has been to
withdraw from retail full-service banking outside of Canada,
except in parts of the Caribbean, and to focus instead on
corporate banking.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO>
WSJ900403-0038
</DOCNO>
<DOCID>
900403-0038.
</DOCID>
<HL>
   ENVIRONMENT
   ----
   By David Stipp
</HL>
<DATE>
04/03/90
</DATE>
<SO>
WALL STREET JOURNAL (J), PAGE B1
</SO>
<CO>
   EUROP
</CO>
<IN>
ENVIRONMENT (ENV)
MARKETING, ADVERTISING (MKT)
CHEMICALS, PLASTICS (CHM)
NUCLEAR POWER, FUEL (NUK)
UTILITIES (UTI)
</IN>
<LP>
   More and More Lawns
   Are Going Organic
                                                                                                       

</LP>
<TEXT>
   ECOLOGICALLY correct yard-care products and services are
springing up like weeds.
   Only about 1% of pesticides are put on lawns, but they
raise special concerns. Children play the most on grass, and
they're "the subgroup of the population most susceptible" to
toxins, notes Susan Cooper, an ecologist with the National
Coalition Against Misuse of Pesticides, an environmental
group. Last week, the U.S. General Accounting Office
underscored concerns by charging that the lawn-care industry
exaggerates pesticide safety.
   Organic offerings include everything from books, such as
"The Chemical-Free Lawn," published last year by Rodale
Press, to rapidly biodegradable pesticides. Rincon-Vitova
Insectories Inc., Oak View, Calif., says its aphid-eating
ladybugs and other insect stand-ins for chemicals are flying
off the shelf.
   NaturaLawn Inc., a Damascus, Md., organic lawn-care
concern, "had to {temporarily} cut off sales last year
because we couldn't handle all the business we were getting,"
says Phil Catron, president. NaturaLawn occasionally uses
chemical herbicide on some tenacious weeds, Mr. Catron says.
But part of the organic approach, he adds, "is educating
people that having a few weeds is not that big a deal."
   Mainstream yard-care concerns also are getting into the
act.
   ChemLawn Services Corp., Columbus, Ohio, says it's
test-marketing a program that uses manure for fertilizer and
no pesticides. Bartlett Tree Experts Co., Stamford, Conn.,
offers an option featuring precisely timed spraying and
pest-attacking insects. The method cuts chemical use by more
than 90%, says Donald Booth, a Bartlett manager.

   Enlisting a Clay Pit
   To Store Solar Energy
                                                                                                       

   ENGINEERS at the University of Massachusetts are planning
a solar energy system based on clay.
   The team plans to capture heat from the sun during the
summer with solar collectors and use it to warm a
100-foot-deep clay deposit near the school's Amherst, Mass.,
campus. In winter, the stored energy would provide as much as
80% of the heating for a new convention center near campus.
   The technique, which could overcome the difficulty of
storing solar energy, was explored by the the U.S. Department
of Energy in the 1970s as a way to heat homes, says team
leader Edward Sunderland. But heat leaked out of the
relatively small systems too fast. The Amherst system's much
larger 100,000-cubic-meter clay deposit is expected to retain
and give back more than 85% of its stored heat, says team
member Dwayne Breger.
   The system would employ six acres of solar collectors
similar to rooftop water heaters. The collectors would heat
water, which would be pumped through underground pipes lacing
the clay to warm it. In winter, the warm clay would heat
water to 140 degrees Fahrenheit before it is pumped to the
convention center.
   The system's estimated cost of about $3.5 million would be
repaid by fuel savings in five to seven years, Mr. Breger
projects. The engineers, whose design work was funded by the
DOE, now are seeking funds to build the system. It would be a
U.S. first, but some 30 such systems already have been built
in Europe, they say.
                                                                                                       

   Ecology Groups Waver
   Over Seals of Approval
                                                                                                       

   IT'S A FAUSTIAN dilemma that's shaping up for some
environmental groups.
   Many of them recently have been approached by retailers
and other concerns proposing to use the groups' names and
logos in product promotions. The companies are offering
royalties or other kinds of payment and a chance for the
groups to spread their messages among consumers. "Right now,
we're being deluged" with such proposals, says Rosemary
Carroll, the Sierra Club's director of development.
   Some groups already make such deals: The Audubon Society
licenses its name to makers of binoculars and birdseed. Black
Sheep Marketing Inc., New York, pays a 25% royalty to the
Rainforest Alliance to use its name in inserts with shower
curtains picturing rain forests. The World Wildlife Fund has
licensed its name to a maker of T-shirts featuring endangered
species.
   But other groups are wrestling with issues raised by the
proposals and haven't yet decided how to handle them. "Our
name could lose all meaning if we don't protect how it is
used," says Ms. Carroll of the Sierra Club, which is now
developing a policy on the matter. For example, she adds, the
group probably won't sign a pact with a company that wants to
promote its plastic-free tampons with the Sierra Club.
                                                                                                       

   Introducing the Annual
   `Green Con Award'
                                                                                                       

   THE LONDON OFFICE of Friends of the Earth has initiated an
annual "Green Con Award."
   The environmental group wants to spotlight examples of
"companies jumping on the green bandwagon when in fact they
are talking gibberish," says a Friends spokeswoman. The first
winner was British Nuclear Fuels PLC for "railing about how
green nuclear power is," she says.
   A British Nuclear spokesman says its recently developed ad
campaign stresses that nuclear plants, unlike conventional
plants, don't pollute the air. "We maintain nuclear power
could contribute to lessening the greenhouse effect," he
says.
   He added that "we don't agree with the criticism that we
are deceiving people. But we derived some amusement from the
award. We would have displayed the trophy in the press
office, but it's so hideous nobody wanted it."
</TEXT>
