<DOC>
<DOCNO>
WSJ900403-0032
</DOCNO>
<DOCID>
900403-0032.
</DOCID>
<HL>
   SEC Chief Criticizes
   Pennsylvania Proposal
   In Anti-Takeover Law
</HL>
<DATE>
04/03/90
</DATE>
<SO>
WALL STREET JOURNAL (J), NO PAGE CITATION
</SO>
<IN>
TENDER OFFERS, MERGERS, ACQUISITIONS (TNM)
</IN>
<GV>
SECURITIES AND EXCHANGE COMMISSION (SEC)
</GV>
<LP>
   WASHINGTON -- Securities and Exchange Commission Chairman
Richard Breeden criticized a Pennsylvania anti-takeover
proposal that would restrict shareholder proxy fights against
management.
   Mr. Breeden, in his first public comment on the state
proposal, said the measure would "virtually eliminate
shareholders' well-established right to replace a board of
directors." Entrenched directors, he said, "could run a
company into the ground" with shareholders powerless to
react.
</LP>
<TEXT>
   The Pennsylvania proposal, which is awaiting final action
by the legislature, would toughen the state's anti-takeover
law to require holders who acquire voting rights for over 20%
of a company's shares to offer to buy all the company's
shares outstanding.
   Supporters say the change would enhance what would become
the nation's stiffest state regulation against hostile
takeovers. Opponents say that under the measure the sponsor
of a proxy resolution trying to line up votes could be forced
to buy the company.
   Mr. Breeden indicated that the SEC would intervene if the
final legislation approved by the state interfered with
federal proxy regulations. "We will not hesitate to seek to
enforce federal interests," he said.
   Mr. Breeden spoke at a meeting of the Council of
Institutional Investors, a group made up mostly of
public-employee pension funds with assets totaling more than
$300 billion.
   Council members, including the statewide pension funds
from California, Florida, Connecticut and Massachusetts,
approved a statement saying they would review their holdings
in Pennsylvania companies if the proposed measure was
adopted.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO>
WSJ900403-0031
</DOCNO>
<DOCID>
900403-0031.
</DOCID>
<HL>
   Corona Ends Accord
   To Sell Some Assets
   To New York Firm
</HL>
<DATE>
04/03/90
</DATE>
<SO>
WALL STREET JOURNAL (J), NO PAGE CITATION
</SO>
<CO>
   ICRA AVL T.POC T.VGR T.CJC
</CO>
<IN>
TENDER OFFERS, MERGERS, ACQUISITIONS (TNM)
</IN>
<LP>
   TORONTO -- Corona Corp. said it ended a previously
reported agreement to sell its industrial mineral assets to
60%-owned Avalon Corp. but continues to negotiate the sale to
Avalon of its 17% interest in Poco Petroleums Ltd.
   The Toronto-based gold-mining company said the agreement
with Avalon was ended after a minority partner in one of
Corona's mineral properties decided to oppose the sale. The
transaction had been conditional on Avalon obtaining 100%
ownership of the assets.
</LP>
<TEXT>
   A Corona spokesman said he expects the sale of the Poco
Petroleums stake to be made at "close to market value,"
giving the transaction an indicated value of about 51.6
million Canadian dollars (US$44.1 million).
   Avalon, an energy exploration and production concern based
in New York, already holds as its main asset a 32% stake in
Poco Petroleums.
   As reported, Poco Petroleums is negotiating a merger with
Voyager Energy Inc. on a share-exchange basis. Avalon said
separately that it has obtained an option to purchase about
32% of Voyager Energy's shares on a fully diluted basis from
CanCapital Corp. for about C$67 million.
   Poco and Voyager are oil and natural-gas concerns based in
Calgary, Alberta. CanCapital is an investment concern based
in Calgary. Avalon said it expects to excercise the option if
the merger between Poco and Voyager is completed. The option
expires Dec. 30.
   On the Toronto Stock Exchange yesterday, Poco Petroleums
shares closed unchanged at C$7.375 ($6.30). Avalon closed at
$5.375, down 12.5 cents, on the New York Stock Exchange.
</TEXT>
