<HL>
   What's News --
   Business and Finance
</HL>
<DATE>
04/03/90
</DATE>
<SO>
WALL STREET JOURNAL (J), PAGE A1
</SO>
<LP>
   GM is to announce today that its president, Robert C.
Stempel, will be named chairman and chief executive,
succeeding Roger B. Smith, who is to retire Aug. 1. Stempel,
56, won't be succeeded as president. Instead, the world's
largest industrial company will promote two executive vice
presidents to vice chairmen.
   ---
</LP>
<TEXT>
   Southland posted a $1.01 billion fourth-quarter loss and
warned it may seek Chapter 11 protection if it can't complete
a financial restructuring.
   ---
   First Executive posted an $835.7 million fourth-quarter
loss, reflecting increased charges for its huge junk-bond
holdings. The firm also said insurance policy surrenders
totaled $559 million in January and February. Also, the SEC
began investigating possible securities violations.
   ---
   U.S. stocks fell after Monday's 6.6% plunge in the Tokyo
market. The dollar continued to post gains, while U.S.
Treasury bonds eased.
                                                                                                       

   Japanese stocks may fall further if the most-recent slide
prompts margin calls, some analysts said. The Nikkei index
finished Tuesday's morning session down 77.19 points.
   ---
   Investor Harold Simmons let his $1 billion offer for
Georgia Gulf expire and now plans to back the company's
revised recapitalization plan.
   ---
   Columbia S&amp;L said declines of 50% or more in the value of
certain junk-bond holdings contributed to its previously
reported insolvency.
   ---
   United Air's unions appeared to be moving toward a
possible accord to buy parent UAL, sources said. Still,
several issues remain unresolved.
   ---
   Fleet/Norstar said troubled loans grew an estimated 50% in
the first quarter, to $600 million. The New England bank had
been considered one of the least vulnerable to the region's
real estate problems.
   ---
   Torchmark withdrew its $6.3 billion takeover bid for
American General and instead will run its own slate for the
insurer's board in a proxy fight. The move, coupled with
increased legal maneuvering, indicated the fight may be long
and messy, observers said.
   ---
   Shearson expects a first-quarter loss of $897 million to
$917 million, a securities industry record, to pay for its
revamping and cost-cutting plan. The firm announced several
new cutbacks as part of the effort.
   ---
   The mortgage-backed securities market received another
blow as Moody's said it may downgrade $26 billion of
securities issued by S&amp;Ls.
   ---
   Xerox said its president, Paul Allaire, will succeed David
Kearns as chief executive officer Aug. 1, though Kearns will
remain chairman.
   ---
   The newest SEC nominee is likely to be Erskine Henderson,
a New York securities lawyer, sources said. He would be the
second black commissioner in the agency's history.
   ---
   Manufacturing remained sluggish in March for the 11th
consecutive month, purchasing managers said. Still, there
were some signs of firming in the sector. Meanwhile,
construction spending climbed 2.6% in February as all sectors
showed gains.
   ---
   Trammell Crow completed a $456 million refinancing deal
with Equitable Real Estate Management as part of an ongoing
restructuring.
   ---
   Markets --
   Stocks: Volume 124,360,000 shares. Dow Jones industrials
2700.45, off 6.76; transportation 1178.88, off 4.26;
utilities 213.85, off 0.81.
   Bonds: Shearson Lehman Hutton Treasury index 3307.45, off
1.12.
   Commodities: Dow Jones futures index 132.42, off 0.02;
spot index 132.35, up 0.45.
   Dollar: 158.95 yen, up 0.60; 1.7009 marks, up 0.0069.
