   Cablevision Systems
   Enters Credit Facility
   With Group of Banks
</HL>
<DATE>
04/03/90
</DATE>
<SO>
WALL STREET JOURNAL (J), NO PAGE CITATION
</SO>
<CO>
   CVC
</CO>
<IN>
TENDER OFFERS, MERGERS, ACQUISITIONS (TNM)
MEDIA, PUBLISHING, BROADCASTING, ELECTRONIC PUBLISHING (MED)
</IN>
<LP>
   WOODBURY, N.Y. -- Cablevision Systems Corp. said it
entered a 10-year, $1.15 billion credit facility with a group
of banks jointly led by Citibank and Toronto Dominion Bank.
   The new facility represents a $250 million increase from
the parent company's existing facility and is expected to
close within 30 days, Cablevision said. A spokesman said the
cash would be used for working capital. He declined to
elaborate.
</LP>
<TEXT>
   Analysts suggested the funds could be used to finance
Cablevision's plan to acquire Gateway Cable from Gilbert
Media Associates L.P. Announced last December, the $102.5
million transaction is expected to close next month and would
give Cablevision an additional 40,000 subscribers. The
company's affiliated systems currently have a 1.5
million-subscriber base.
   The funds also might be put toward Cablevision's
involvement in the Sky Cable plan, announced early this year,
analysts said. Cablevision will spend $75 million over four
years in a joint venture with Rupert Murdoch's News Corp.,
General Motors Corp.'s Hughes Communications unit, and
General Electric Co.'s National Broadcasting Co. unit.
