<HL>
   GM To Name Today
   Stempel as Chairman
   And Chief Executive
   ----
   By Paul Ingrassia
   Staff Reporter of The Wall Street Journal
</HL>
<DATE>
04/03/90
</DATE>
<SO>
WALL STREET JOURNAL (J), PAGE A3
</SO>
<CO>
   WNEWS GM GMH
</CO>
<IN>
AUTOMOBILES (AUT)
</IN>
<LP>
   DETROIT -- General Motors Corp. will announce today that
Robert C. Stempel, its 56-year-old president, will be named
chairman and chief executive officer, succeeding Roger B.
Smith, who is to retire Aug. 1.
   Mr. Stempel, it was learned, won't be succeeded as
president of GM. Instead, the auto maker will promote two
executive vice presidents to vice chairmen: John F. Smith Jr.
and Robert J. Schultz. Both will retain their current duties,
Mr. Smith as head of GM's international operations and Mr.
Schultz as head of technical staffs and GM's two big
subsidiaries, Electronic Data Systems Corp. and GM Hughes
Electronics.
</LP>
<TEXT>
   Lloyd E. Reuss, another executive vice president who's
responsible for GM's huge North American auto operations,
will become president of those operations, essentially a
change in title. However, he will also gain additional
responsibility by overseeing GM's huge components operations.
Those operations will continue to report to William E.
Hoglund, who continues as executive vice president but now
will report to Mr. Reuss.
   Two other executive vice presidents, Robert T. O'Connell
and F. Alan Smith, will remain in their current posts, Mr.
O'Connell as head of financial operations and Alan Smith as
head of corporate staff functions. None of the Smiths --
Roger, John or Alan -- is related.
   Mr. Stempel has long been regarded as the favorite to
succeed Roger Smith as chairman of the world's largest
industrial company, but his appointment marks a significant
departure from tradition at GM. Mr. Stempel is an engineer.
GM usually draws its chairmen from its financial ranks.
   The company's theory has been that only financial men can
enforce cost discipline at a company where spending is
measured in the tens of billions of dollars. If GM's
engineers were left to their own devices, the reasoning goes,
they would overspend like unfettered Pentagon generals,
bringing mediocre earnings to a company where the boast has
long been: "General Motors doesn't make cars. It makes
money."
   But that theory has been blown apart during this decade.
GM spent more than $70 billion in capital outlays during the
1980s, but the company's U.S. market share has dropped more
than 10% and for three years in a row earnings fell behind
those of its smaller rival, Ford Motor Co. Many at GM are
convinced that the company needs a "product man" to revive
its fortunes in its largest market.
   Mr. Stempel has that reputation, even though his track
record is somewhat hard to guage. He has had six different
jobs at GM in the past 11 years.
   The jobs that brought Mr. Stempel to the fore were his
leadership of GM's Buick-Oldsmobile-Cadillac group, which
makes most of the company's large cars, between 1984 and
1986, and head of truck and international operations in 1986
and 1987.
   The BOC group adopted a decentralized operating structure
that has made it far more effective than its counterpart, the
Chevrolet-Pontiac-Canada group. BOC leads in product quality
and in profitability by a wide margin. GM's international
operations, meanwhile, have turned the corner to handsome
profitability in recent years, especially in Europe.
   Because of his relatively young age, Mr. Stempel, like
Chairman Smith, can be expected to have a long tenure at the
helm of GM. His most significant challenge will be turning
around the company's troubled North American auto operations,
which have suffered from a decade of decline.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO>
WSJ900403-0010
</DOCNO>
<DOCID>
900403-0010.
</DOCID>
<HL>
   International:
   Kohl Reassures
   East Germans
   On Mark Plan
   ----
   By Terence Roth
   Staff Reporter of The Wall Street Journal
</HL>
<DATE>
04/03/90
</DATE>
<SO>
WALL STREET JOURNAL (J), PAGE A17
</SO>
<CO>
   EUROP
</CO>
<IN>
MONETARY NEWS, FOREIGN EXCHANGE, TRADE (MON)
INTERNATIONAL ECONOMIC NEWS AND STATISTICS (IEN)
FOREIGN-EXCHANGE MARKETS (FRX)
</IN>
<LP>
   FRANKFURT, West Germany -- Chancellor Helmut Kohl rushed
to neutral ground after a Bundesbank proposal to strictly
limit the exchange of East German savings into West German
marks provoked warnings of social unrest in East Germany and
a round of criticism in Bonn.
   "No decisions or commitments whatsoever have been made,"
Mr. Kohl declared in a statement. The chancellor said the
Bundesbank recommendation would be studied carefully, but
stressed that preparatory talks were still under way.
</LP>
<TEXT>
   "I expressly acknowledge my responsibility for the people
of the DDR {East Germany}. I repeatedly underlined my pledge
to solidarity during the DDR election campaign, and I stand
by this," Mr. Kohl asserted. He reaffirmed plans to achieve a
currency union with East Germany this summer, but offered no
specific conversion rates. Talks on monetary union will
resume with the formation of a new East German government,
Mr. Kohl said.
   The controversial Bundesbank plan would limit the 1-for-1
conversion rate for East Germany's 160 billion East German
marks in savings to 2,000 West German marks ($1,181.40) per
person. The central bank also stipulated that the remainder
of savings -- as well as wages, pensions and debt -- be
converted at a rate of one West German mark for two East
German marks. This would minimize strains on East German
industry and lessen the inflationary impact on West German
monetary policy, officials explained.
   Chancellor Kohl had promised a 1-for-1 rate for savers
while campaigning for East German conservative candidates
last month. East German leaders say their electorate had
widely interpreted the assurance as meaning that all savings,
wages and pensions of the 16 million East Germans would be
converted at the more-favorable rate.
   The discord over the knotty currency issue has complicated
Chancellor Kohl's hitherto mostly smooth progress toward
German unity, capped by the conservative victory in East
Germany's March 18 elections. Finance Minister Theo Waigel
has endorsed the Bundesbank's plan, but other senior Bonn
cabinet members were keeping their distance. Foreign Minister
Hans-Dietrich Genscher said in a radio interview yesterday
the Bundesbank recommendations "won't be the last word and
can't be the last word."
   The Social Democratic opposition party in Bonn was quick
to exploit the dispute. Oskar Lafontaine, the SPD's candidate
for chancellor in West Germany's December elections, accused
Mr. Kohl of breaking a promise in what he called "voter
deception" after many East German voters chose a three-party
alliance led by the East German Christian Democratic Union on
the basis of Mr. Kohl's conversion promise.
   East Germans officials fear that a dilution of East German
savings and incomes would impoverish normal wage earners.
They predicted demonstrations and a new wave of emigration if
the Bundesbank plan were adopted. East German union leaders
warned of imminent strikes by protesting workers unless a
clear signal was sent from Bonn.
   East Germany's premier-designate, Lothar de Maiziere, said
yesterday his East German Christian Democrats are sticking to
its promise for a broad 1-for-1 exchange.
   "We don't believe it possible that salaries, wages, and
pensions can be treated on a 1-for-2 basis," Mr. de Maiziere
said in East Berlin. He observed that average East German
wages already amount to only one-third of West German levels.
   West German monetary officials worry that the vast gap in
West German and East German productivity levels could unleash
inflation.
   Bonn already is expected to have to come up with as much
as 50 billion marks a year to rebuild East Germany's
crumbling infrastructure. And because Bonn would have to foot
the bill for any East German crisis -- such as mass
unemployment or a collapse of the social security system --
Mr. Kohl is seen walking a fine line between promises to the
East German electorate and the advice of his monetary
experts.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO>
WSJ900403-0009
</DOCNO>
<DOCID>
900403-0009.
</DOCID>
