</DOCNO>
<DOCID>
900403-0006.
</DOCID>
<HL>
   Fannie Mae Unveils
   Instrument to Boost
   Affordable Housing
</HL>
<DATE>
04/03/90
</DATE>
<SO>
WALL STREET JOURNAL (J), PAGE C8
</SO>
<CO>
   FNM
</CO>
<IN>
FINANCIAL, ACCOUNTING, LEASING (FIN)
BANKS (BNK)
REAL ESTATE, REITS, LAND DEVELOPMENT (REL)
HEAVY CONSTRUCTION; INDUSTRIAL AND COMMERCIAL (CON)
SAVINGS AND LOANS, THRIFTS, CREDIT UNIONS (SAL)
</IN>
<LP>
   WASHINGTON -- The Federal National Mortgage Association
introduced a new mortgage-backed security to increase
below-market mortgage funds designated for low-income buyers
by the Federal Home Loan Banks.
   The financial instrument, called Fannie Mae Affordables,
allows members of the 12 regional Home Loan Banks to pool
special below-market loans originated under two programs
mandated by last year's savings-and-loan rescue legislation.
</LP>
<TEXT>
   The loans are funded with advances from the Home Loan
Banks. Under the Affordable Housing Program, the regional
banks provide subsidized advances to member institutions,
while funds for the Community Investment Program are advanced
at cost. The Affordable Housing Program is expected to total
more than $78 million this year.
   Mortgages originated under the low and moderate income
program can be swapped for Fannie Mae Affordables, which are
single-lender pools as low as $250,000. Institutions can keep
Fannie Mae Affordables as an investment or sell them back to
the regional banks to repay advances. Pools of less than $1
million won't be traded freely on the open market.
   Larry H. Dale, Fannie Mae's senior vice president of
multifamily finance and housing initiatives, said the company
has been working out details of the program with the Home
Loan Banks since the fall. "One of the real beauties of this
approach is that it makes it possible for the Home Loan Banks
and their members to work within an environment they know
well," he said.
   Fannie Mae, a federally chartered, publicly traded
corporation, operates a secondary market for mortgage loans,
buying loans from lenders, packaging them into securities and
selling some to investors while holding others in its
portfolio.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO>
WSJ900403-0005
</DOCNO>
<DOCID>
900403-0005.
</DOCID>
<HL>
   Technology:
   AT&amp;T Unit Unveils
   A Minicomputer
   And Other Products
</HL>
<DATE>
04/03/90
</DATE>
<SO>
WALL STREET JOURNAL (J), PAGE B4
</SO>
<CO>
   T PYRD
</CO>
<IN>
COMPUTERS AND INFORMATION TECHNOLOGY (CPR)
</IN>
<LP>
   NEW YORK -- AT&amp;T Computer Systems unveiled several new
computer and communications products, including a powerful
entrant into the increasingly competitive market for
minicomputers handling transactions.
   The new mini, which had been expected, comes in a series
called the AT&amp;T System 7000 and is being marketed to
companies with heavy transaction processing needs such as
hotels, financial-services companies and phone companies. It
is also the product of a yearlong collaboration between the
American Telephone &amp; Telegraph Co. unit and Pyramid
Technology Corp., Mountain View, Calif., which designed and
builds the machine.
</LP>
<TEXT>
   The 7000 is AT&amp;T's first minicomputer product employing
reduced-instruction-set-computing (RISC) architecture. RISC
designs offer faster computing since the computer needs fewer
internal instructions to perform tasks. The computer also
uses the Unix software operating system designed by AT&amp;T Bell
Laboratories and is said to handle 170 transactions per
second and up to 122 million instructions per second.
   James E. Clark, AT&amp;T product management and development
vice president for minicomputers and high performance
systems, said the new line expands the performance of AT&amp;T's
products beyond its current top-of-the-line 3B minicomputers.
This, he added, should make AT&amp;T competitive with low-end
mainframe computers made by International Business Machines
Corp. and Amdahl Corp. and RISC-based systems that AT&amp;T
expects its competitors such as Digital Equipment Corp. to
bring out in 1991.
   Pricing for the new computer ranges from $88,000 for a
system, including software, that handles 128 computer users,
to $225,000 for a system tying together 1,000 users.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
